Democracy without Popular Connection
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this has happened everywhere in the world.
Somehow people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of elections for the European Parliament, voter turnout was so ridiculously low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the votes as "winners".
Majority governments are formed on the basis of minorities, from Holland via Finland to Argentina and Japan.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10 % of the electorate. In fact, half of the voters in the USA have not even registered to participate in the election; of those who have registered, half do not vote; of those who vote, less than half vote for the election winner.
Even Tony Blair's "dam-breaking" majority in the House of Commons of Great Britain stands on shaky ground: The Labour Party only received just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24 % of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look clearly different than they did twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
An answer might be that voters distrust political parties.
The electoral democracy functions in most countries based on the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who stand for certain packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "campaign platform."
Due to a number of reasons, this long-proven practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages put together by the parties, they want to pick out and choose something for themselves.
Moreover, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cadres of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have distanced the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority now plays the party game.
This increases public suspicion towards political parties, not least because, like professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by taxpayers, this is resented.
However, without financial support from the state, parties would have to find money through channels that are often highly dubious, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last few decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thus have the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, fairly independent development comes into play.
People today are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they have become accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
But as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the results of the election they have cast their votes for.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful consideration.
The consumer as a voter, however, will not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "Direct Action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, this could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are also non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, but they still seem to be more closely connected to the citizens.
Furthermore, there is naturally the option to completely disengage and leave politics to the experts in order to focus on other aspects of life.
The latter probably carries the greatest risks, because it promotes the creeping authoritarianism that is a sign of our times.
However, the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also create a rather insecure situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some would like to break the knot by increasing direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There would still be much to be said for clinging to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to link them more closely again to the citizenry.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter participation could prove to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and inject more life into elections and representative governments.
Yet this is probably not enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the primary concern of all those for whom freedom is at the heart of the constitution must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
